metadata.name: Richter #356
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

metadata.name: Primitifs systématiques #14
metadata.description:
Primitifs systématiques is the first generative instalment of David Umemoto’s studies of space and volume. Placed at the crux of brutalism and minimalism, these structures based on the original stackable concrete piece Primitif 04 evoke impossible paths yet to be explored. 

The original Primitif 04 has been both preserved and dented, conserved and enhanced. It is still here. But it cannot be found, only encountered. Throughout your explorations of the Primitifs systématiques, you will find that its original shapes have been multiplied, rotated, re-ordered to create new structures. After spending some time exploring its paths, when you stop looking for it, you will realize that 04 is still here, intact.

Lines of work chosen for this piece also draw a perspective. The orientation of the primitives pulls directly towards an intense source of light. Sometimes it is visible, sometimes it is not. This perfect alignment is a call to life. They who look at the sunrise with relief cannot be anything but hopeful. But how can we project life on a concrete behemoth? Stand long enough in front of it, and you too will see that we have no choice but to.

----

Primitifs systématiques is the generative art genesis piece of David Umemoto. It was built in collaboration with Anaglyphic. It is the first collaborative spatial token made available on the anaver.se.

metadata.name: color combinations #127
metadata.description:
the 'color combinations' series was developed as an exercise of combining colors from a single defined palette and the attempt to make all 15 selected colors being able to work within each other.

the constant pursuit for perfectionism made me design more than 200 tentatives of creating a perfect circle, and therefore the circle is the rarest output for the series.

i hope this series serves as a reference and inspire everyone out there.

2,340 possible combinations.
the closer the shape to the circle the rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%.
the bigger the shape the rarer - ranging from 30% to 20%.
beige and black colors are rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%

metadata.name: TIMEFRAMES #39
metadata.description:
‘What if you could take a photo of time?’

As a photographer myself, the act of taking photos is the act of freezing moments of time. Moments that will no longer ever be here. Each layer represents not only 3 aspects of time (hours, minutes and seconds) but also a very important aspect of photography: the light. Combining these two instances: the visual interpretation of light and the generative aspect of time - I present ‘TIMEFRAMES’.

12 selected colors. 5,688,900 possible combinations.

The less layers the rarer - ranging from 100% to 18%
All timeframes that have 42 on it like 4:20:00, 4:42:42, 4:20:42 are rarer - ranging from 50% to 42%
The darker the colors the rarer - ranging from 100% to 89%

Click on the image to Download. Created with @PureSpider’s template.

José Gasparian.
2022.

metadata.name: MONOLITH #147
metadata.description:
Very limited facts are known about these strange monolithic structures. Black, rectilinear, similar to obsidian stone but made of strange materials. According to legend, an ancient civilization of high intelligence, called the Explorers of Latent Space, distributed hundreds of monoliths throughout time and space in order to study the behavior of species in the infinite Universe.

Some say that it is the divine intelligence of God. Others say that, in spite of their objectual and material condition, the monoliths possess their own consciousness and an intelligence beyond the natural and artificial. Their purpose or objective, to this day, remains a mystery.

_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_

this work is done only with code, using threejs and p5js
it might be a bit slow on low-end devices, be patient

metadata.name: Ephemeral Fountain v1.0 #157
metadata.description:
This project originated with me thinking about how to do very realistic glass spheres that can be manipulated and moved within the THREE.js environment. Mixing that with several hundred ephemeral non-glass objects which are moving in a fountain-like flow, adding reflection and refraction to the glass, and combining it all in a physical existence which I playfully only impose on the non-glass objects nearby... in this world, glass can move through glass, with interesting effects similar to diamonds firing when light hits them at just the right angle! 

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3% six, 1% seven and 1% eight. Happy hunting!

metadata.name: Neo-Retro Building #34
metadata.description:
"Depicting architectural"

The idea of depicting architectural designs for buildings in the future dates back to the 19th century with the rise of industrialization and advancements in technology. Architects and artists began to imagine what cities and buildings of the future might look like, often featuring towering skyscrapers, flying cars, and sleek, modern designs.

One early example is the 1889 World's Fair in Paris, which featured a "City of the Future" exhibit that showcased a vision of a highly-developed, technologically advanced metropolis. In the early 20th century, architects such as Le Corbusier proposed designs for "machine for living" buildings that were meant to be efficient and functional, with an emphasis on clean lines and minimal ornamentation.

In the decades that followed, architects and designers continued to create images of future buildings and cities, with an increasing focus on sustainability and eco-friendliness. This can be seen in concepts like the "smart city," which envisions cities that are highly connected and responsive to the needs of citizens, and designs for buildings that incorporate renewable energy sources and green spaces.

metadata.name: Memory #250
metadata.description:
"Memory" is an experiment in the dynamic interplay of soulful colors and forms. 
It is an exploration of smooth animation blending interesting fluid shapes. 
The piece is a continuous flow of forms and hues that seamlessly transition. 
The viewer can interactively zoom in and out and navigate to explore the full space of the artwork.
Furthermore the aspect ratio can be change to vary the framing of the piece, generating new impressions.
This invites the viewer to fully immerse themselves in the piece and experience it from different perspectives.
The name "Memory" reflects the intention to display an abstract representation of memories of a machine.
The colors aim to evoke a sense of emotion and depth. 

I created this work using twgl.js on a single fragment shader, my recent technique of choice. 

I hope you enjoy interacting with "Memory" and exploring the different aspects of the piece.

This piece uses webgl, it can thus only be viewed on browsers implementing webgl.

License: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Dependencies: 
- twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library (MIT license)
- psrdnoise.glsl (MIT license)
- isMobile (Unlicense)
For more information, view the license file

Interactions
'-' to zoom in. 
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'1' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to portrait format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the frame.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash.
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.
